WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:07.280
As of this video, it's been 478 days since we&nbsp;
started wearing barefoot shoes to do almost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:09.041
everything, except...

00:00:11.041 --> 00:00:15.415
My theory is that my feet&nbsp;
were not ready to play sports like pickleball&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:21.120
or tennis in barefoot shoes, as I have pretty&nbsp;
heavy and clumsy feet. In the last year or so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:26.800
since picking up tennis, I've been making do&nbsp;
with my old worn down pair of running shoes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:32.720
But running shoes are designed for moving in&nbsp;
one direction — forward. While tennis requires&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:38.800
unpredictable movement in all directions.&nbsp;
So like a proper tennis player wannabe,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:44.240
whenever I'm not playing well, I blame my&nbsp;
equipment. To bring my game to the next level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:50.960
perhaps it's time to get new shoes. The last 478&nbsp;
days of getting used to barefoot shoes were just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:57.360
preparation for this moment. So here I have with&nbsp;
me the Tolos Soleil Transition. We've been playing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:02.320
tennis with these for a couple of months and&nbsp;
not gonna to lie, we had to make a few tweaks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:07.360
to make it work. But you'll find out why when&nbsp;
it comes to wearing barefoot shoes for tennis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:12.033
we feel like transitional is just the&nbsp;
right word to sum up our experience.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:20.400
For my first pair of barefoot shoes for tennis,&nbsp;
I'm looking at three things. One, if I don't like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:26.160
the way a shoe looks, then I'm less likely to want&nbsp;
to put it on. Ideally, I don't want something that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:32.480
screams barefoot shoes. And in this regard, these&nbsp;
have a simple, clean design and do not feel out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:39.200
of place with my usual athleisure style. Two,&nbsp;
apart from lacking lateral support and the fact&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:44.960
that they are falling apart, my biggest problem&nbsp;
with my old running shoes is the same problem I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:51.360
have with conventional shoes in general. The toe&nbsp;
box is too narrow. I'm sure most people know the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:56.720
feeling where your feet have expanded after a day&nbsp;
of walking and your toes are hurting from being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.920
crammed inside of your shoes. After getting used&nbsp;
to barefoot shoes, that's what it always feels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:07.600
like when I'm wearing these or other non foot-shaped shoes. 
I just can't wait to get home and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:13.760
finally take them off. In comparison, you can see&nbsp;
how much roomier the design of the toe box is on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:20.560
pair of foot-shaped shoes. This allows our toes to&nbsp;
splay naturally. As far as off the court comfort,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:25.760
things are pretty straightforward. These are&nbsp;
probably the least constrictive shoes that we own,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:30.560
and I've walked a whole day in these with&nbsp;
no problems. But tennis shoes usually have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:35.840
reinforced structures for stability and a lot&nbsp;
of padding for a snug feet, making it feel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:41.360
like your feet are one with the shoes. With&nbsp;
barefoot shoes, there's a delicate balance.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.800
You want your toes to be able to splay, but too&nbsp;
much wiggle room could mean a lack of that locked&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:53.120
down feeling that is ideal for higher intensity&nbsp;
movements. On the court, we are reminded that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:59.440
is not a serious tennis shoe. It's not only got a&nbsp;
wide toe box, it's also generous with the vertical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:05.840
space. The high volume makes it quite comfortable&nbsp;
as a casual shoe off the court, but not the most agile&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:12.320
feeling shoe on the court. And as a not so agile&nbsp;
person, whenever I'm playing tennis with these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:18.480
I kept having the thought that I should have gone&nbsp;
half a size smaller for a more athletic fit. Glo&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:23.840
suggested tying a runner's knot, which helped&nbsp;
to make it feel more secure at the ankles, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:29.280
it didn't directly address the problem of having&nbsp;
too much wriggle room at the forefoot. Then he had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:35.600
the idea of filling some of that excess space by&nbsp;
using insoles. We tried insoles from our other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:42.080
pair of barefoot shoes from Feelgrounds. These are&nbsp;
only 3 mm, but I could already feel a noticeable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:48.000
improvement. So, we tried thicker sports insoles&nbsp;
from our old running shoes, which gave more of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.480
that locked down feeling, and it made playing tennis&nbsp;
in these much more enjoyable. One more benefit of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.480 --> 00:04:00.880
using sport specific insoles is that they provide&nbsp;
a small boost in cushion and bounce, which is nice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:07.280
for my clumsy feet as these shoes have relatively&nbsp;
firm soles for a barefoot shoe. But that may also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:13.040
be because these have thicker soles than that of&nbsp;
most barefoot shoes. Which brings us to the third&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:20.400
point. Most barefoot shoes have a sole height of&nbsp;
under 10 mm. Granted, not all midsoles are made&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:26.400
the same, but on paper that is a bit thinner&nbsp;
than what we are comfortable with for sports.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:32.320
For my first barefoot shoes for tennis, I wanted&nbsp;
slightly more cushion than the industry average.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:37.440
These shoes, specifically the transition sole&nbsp;
that we have, have a pretty rare stack height&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:44.880
of 13 mm. Tolos markets the transition soles as the&nbsp;
option for those who are new to barefoot shoes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:50.240
And while we are not new to barefoot shoes in that&nbsp;
sense, we are new to wearing barefoot shoes when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:56.080
playing sports. Considering I'm just learning the&nbsp;
game of tennis and playing at a low intensity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:02.080
all I want is a pair of shoes that don't strangle&nbsp;
my feet and are cushioned enough for sports. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:08.640
these are my transitional shoes. Would this be&nbsp;
my pick in a year or two from now? Honestly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:14.880
unless I don't get any better at tennis, the&nbsp;
answer is probably not. These are casual shoes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:21.360
that I can comfortably place some tennis in. But&nbsp;
if and when I get good enough at the game, I will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:26.960
want something that is more of a tennis-first&nbsp;
barefoot shoe, which as far as we know doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:33.200
really exist at the moment. Of course, I'm not the&nbsp;
only one in this story. When Glo first started&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:39.200
playing tennis with me, he would wear his usual&nbsp;
narrow tennis shoes, but after a few sessions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:44.960
he realized maybe it wasn't worth it, considering&nbsp;
how low intensity our sessions were, where he's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:50.560
mostly in a coaching capacity anyway. He even&nbsp;
tried wearing his Feelgrounds canvas sneakers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:56.640
instead, but was worried that the fabric wouldn't&nbsp;
be durable enough. In the end, he mostly played&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:03.520
barefooted, which is obviously not ideal. But now&nbsp;
and for the foreseeable future, the Tolos Soleils are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:09.360
a comfortable barefoot option for him to coach me&nbsp;
in. So, what do we think about barefoot shoes for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:15.840
court sports like tennis or pickleball? Here are&nbsp;
our suggestions based on our limited experience.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:21.760
First, know your body and consider the intensity&nbsp;
you'll be playing at. We are relatively active&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:27.040
and injury-free, and we know we are not going&nbsp;
to be playing at a very high intensity. If you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:33.440
are in similar shoes, no pun intended, we think&nbsp;
barefoot shoes are perfectly fine. Unless you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:38.800
plan to slide around all over the court, we think&nbsp;
they can be great as training shoes or for playing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:44.320
casual pickleball and tennis. But finding the&nbsp;
right barefoot shoes suitable for your game can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:50.560
be the tricky bit. Most barefoot shoes by design&nbsp;
have relatively thin soles. We have counted out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:56.640
many models of athletic barefoot shoes because the&nbsp;
sole height seemed a little low for our liking.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:02.000
Our second suggestion, which is something we&nbsp;
realized during the course of trying these shoes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.320
is to not count out insoles. Using padded insoles&nbsp;
can feel a little counter to the whole concept&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:14.400
and culture of barefoot shoes. But if you really&nbsp;
like the shape and comfort of a particular shoe,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:19.760
or if it just feels a little too roomy for&nbsp;
sports, insoles have the potential to make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.880
it work. For now, we are happy playing&nbsp;
with these, but we'll be on the lookout&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:35.520
for a more ideal foot-shaped shoe for tennis.&nbsp;
Hopefully, they'll arrive before I turn pro.

